\par \hich\af1\dbch\af23\loch\f1 Q: How do I add IRC operators?
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af23\loch\f1 A:\hich\af1\dbch\af23\loch\f1  Adding operators is a bit harder than before, but the concept is the same as most IRCDs. Browse
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af23\loch\f1    to where ignitionServer is installed and open ircx.conf in Notepad. Somewhere in the file, add
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af23\loch\f1    an "O" line. It is formatted like this:
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af23\loch\f1      O:<hostname>:<password>:<username>:<operator-flags>:<connection-class>
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af23\loch\f1    Hostname is the standard IRC hostname of the user (wildcards permitted). For example, if someone
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af23\loch\f1    used AOL, their hostname/hostmask would be *@*aol.com. Password and username \hich\af1\dbch\af23\loch\f1 are
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af23\loch\f1    self-explanitory. Operator flags can be any of the following: osixkrRDCcKB. Most are standard
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af23\loch\f1    operator flags, however there are a few you should be aware of. R and D allow the oper to
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af23\loch\f1    restart and die (stop) the server. They still require the d\hich\af1\dbch\af23\loch\f1 ie/restart password. 
\par 
